    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-03-25T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-03-25T06:00:00-05:00" n="476"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d476">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/1883: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Bulgaria</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Earle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sofia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-03-25T13:00:00+02:00"
                            >March 25, 1940—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 3:42 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>24. Asked Foreign Minister<note n="94" xml:id="d476fn94">Ivan Popov, since
                        February 19, 1940, in Cabinet of Bogdan Filov.</note> during long discussion
                    if he believed that Russia would overrun Bessarabia in order to retrieve
                    military prestige seriously damaged in Finland. Foreign Minister answered
                    definitely no, giving following reasons. First, Bessarabia has no important
                    strategic objectives such as Finnish positions; Russia already has more than
                    enough undeveloped land and plenty of coast on Black Sea. Second, Germany would
                    oppose such invasion as war would interrupt vital flow of oil to Germany. Third,
                    Stalin wants no war as his position in peace much more secure than in war
                    surrounded by powerful generals. Foreign Minister thinks sturdy Finnish
                    resistance was great surprise to Russian general staff who expected slight
                    resistance not amounting to war.</p>
                <p>Personally believe Foreign Minister neglected to mention importance of
                    controlling the mouth of the Danube.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Earle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
